        <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What is the world record for a dead hang?</h3>
          <p>The Guinness World Record for the longest duration in the dead hang position is 80 minutes and 41 seconds, set by Kenta Adachi of Japan on 18 November 2022. He broke the previous record of 16 minutes 3 seconds held by Harald Riise of Norway in 2021.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What is the female dead hang world record?</h3>
          <p>Guinness lists the longest duration in the dead hang position as an open category, and it recognises age group female records such as the oldest woman to hold a dead hang. Elite female climbers commonly hold dead hangs beyond 3 minutes in training.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>Can a normal person hang for 5 minutes?</h3>
          <p>A 5-minute dead hang is extremely difficult. The average untrained adult holds 30-60 seconds. Reaching 5 minutes requires months of dedicated grip training, specific forearm endurance programming and mental conditioning. Fewer than 1% of regular gym-goers achieve this.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>How long can the average person dead hang?</h3>
          <p>The average untrained person dead hangs for 20-40 seconds. Men average 30-60 seconds and women 20-40 seconds. With 4-8 weeks of training, most people reach 60-90 seconds. The world record of over 80 minutes is more than 100 times longer.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>Is a 3 minute dead hang impressive?</h3>
          <p>A 3-minute dead hang is impressive by any standard. This places you well above 95% of the general population. Most trained gym-goers never reach 3 minutes. It requires dedicated forearm endurance training beyond general fitness work.</p>
        </div>

